## State Collection Best Practices

### ✅ Always use collectAsStateWithLifecycle() for StateFlow
`collectAsStateWithLifecycle()` automatically pauses collection when the app goes to background (lifecycle < STARTED) and resumes when it comes back. This prevents unnecessary work and resource leaks.
```kotlin
import androidx.lifecycle.compose.collectAsStateWithLifecycle

// ✅ GOOD — stops collecting in background
val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()

// ❌ BAD — keeps collecting even when app is in background
val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsState()
```

Required dependency in each feature module's `build.gradle.kts`:
```kotlin
implementation(libs.androidx.lifecycle.runtime.compose)
```

### ✅ Use collectLatest with LaunchedEffect for SharedFlow
One-shot events (errors, navigation signals) use `SharedFlow` collected via `LaunchedEffect` — this is unaffected by lifecycle since it already stops when the composable leaves composition.
```kotlin
LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    viewModel.error.collectLatest { error ->
        snackbarHostState.showSnackbar(error.message.toString())
    }
}
```

### ❌ Don't collect in top-level composables repeatedly
```kotlin
// BAD - collects multiple times
val item by viewModel.item.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()
val items by viewModel.items.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()
val loading by viewModel.loading.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()

// GOOD - single sealed state
val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()
```

